  "prompt": "How do I prevent iMovie for iPad from cropping the top and bottom off my video that was originally taken in portrait orientation?",
  "response": "When editing a video that was shot in portrait orientation on iMovie for iPad, you may find that the top and bottom are cropped by default, as iMovie tries to fit the video into a landscape format. Here\u2019s how you can avoid this cropping and maintain the original aspect ratio:\n\n1. **Open iMovie**: Launch the iMovie app on your iPad.\n\n2. **Create a New Project**: Tap the plus sign (+) to start a new project and then tap \"Movie\".\n\n3. **Import Your Video**: Select the portrait video from your library that you want to edit and add it to your project.\n\n4. **Adjust Video Settings**:\n   - Tap on the video clip in the timeline to select it.\n   - Make sure the video inspector options are visible (you may need to tap the clip again to bring up these options).\n   - Tap the magnifying glass icon labeled \u201cPinch to zoom\u201d or any similar cropping tool that appears (this may vary slightly based on iMovie version).\n\n5. **Reframe the Video**:\n   - Use your fingers to pinch inwards on the video to zoom out.\n   - Center your video within the frame to ensure it fits without cropping the top and bottom. \n\n6. **Set the Aspect Ratio**:\n   - iMovie typically uses a 16:9 aspect ratio. Before finalizing your video, confirm the aspect ratio settings in the project settings, if available.\n   - Alternatively, if you can enable \"Fit\" or \"Crop to Fill\" depending on the options, choose \u201cFit\u201d to maintain the entire video in the frame without cropping.\n\n7. **Position and Scale**: Drag the video around to center it and make sure the entire video content is visible as you\u2019d like without cropping.\n\n8. **Preview Your Edit**: Play the video in the preview window to ensure it looks correct and that there\u2019s no unwanted cropping.\n\n9. **Export the Video**: Once you\u2019re satisfied with how the video looks, you can proceed to export your final project.\n\nRemember, iMovie does have limitations in terms of flexibility with aspect ratios, and sometimes additional third-party editing software may be needed for more advanced settings. If you are facing continuous issues with layout constraints, consider using apps that are more oriented towards supporting various aspect ratios like Adobe Premiere Rush or LumaFusion.",
